#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:10
msgid ""
"1.4 The Renormalization Group: From Microscopic Spins to Macroscopic "
"Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:12
msgid ""
"So far we have seen how the Ising model describes a system of interacting"
" spins and how the Boltzmann distribution governs its equilibrium "
"behaviour. But what happens when we **zoom out, i.e.** when we stop "
"looking at every individual spin and instead focus on larger, coarse-"
"grained blocks? This question is answered by the **Renormalization Group "
"(RG)**, a powerful framework from statistical physics that explains why "
"the laws of nature appear simple at different scales and why seemingly "
"different systems can behave identically near a critical point. "
"Remarkably, the RG also provides a deep physical analogy for the "
"hierarchical feature learning performed by deep neural networks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:14
msgid "The Core Idea: Coarse-Graining"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:15
msgid ""
"Imagine a two-dimensional Ising model on a square lattice. Instead of "
"observing every spin, we partition the lattice into blocks of size $2 "
"\\times 2$, and replace each block with a single effective spin. This is "
"called **coarse-graining**. The new effective spins interact with each "
"other according to new, renormalized couplings $J'$ and fields $h'$. The "
"key insight is that the rules of the universe – the Hamiltonian – change "
"when you change your observational scale."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:17
msgid "The process of coarse-graining is repeated iteratively:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:19
msgid "Start with spins at the finest scale."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:20
msgid ""
"Apply a coarse-graining transformation (e.g., block averaging or majority"
" rule)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:21
msgid "Obtain a new, coarser Hamiltonian with new parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:22
msgid "Repeat."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:24
msgid "This defines a **flow** in the space of Hamiltonians."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:26
msgid "Fixed Points and Universality"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:27
msgid ""
"As the RG flow is iterated, the parameters $(J, h, \\ldots)$ move through"
" the parameter space. The system may eventually reach a **fixed point**– "
"a point where further coarse-graining leaves the Hamiltonian unchanged. "
"Fixed points correspond to **critical points** of the system, where the "
"correlation length diverges and the system becomes scale-invariant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:29
msgid ""
"The profound consequence is **universality**: many different microscopic "
"systems (different metals, different liquids) flow to the same fixed "
"point. This is why we can compute properties of a liquid without knowing "
"every detail of the molecules – the relevant physics at the macroscopic "
"scale is determined by the fixed point, not by the microscopic details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:31
msgid "The Renormalization Group and Deep Learning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:32
msgid ""
"The RG provides a striking physical analogy for the **hierarchical "
"feature learning** performed by stacked RBMs (Deep Belief Networks, see "
"Section [4.3 Beyond Single Layers: Stacking for Deep Learning](kpp-"
"theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md))."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid "Renormalization Group"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid "Deep Belief Network (Stacked RBM)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid "Coarse-grain spin blocks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid "Pooling / abstracting features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid "New effective couplings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid "Higher-layer weights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid "Fixed point (scale invariance)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid "Top-level, most abstract representation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid "Universality (same fixed point from many microstates)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md
msgid ""
"Generalisation: same high-level features emerge from many training "
"examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:41
msgid ""
"In a DBN, each new hidden layer can be seen as a **coarse-graining "
"operation** on the distribution of features from the layer below. The "
"first hidden layer captures local edges and corners; the second layer "
"combines these into mid-level shapes; the third layer forms high-level "
"object representations. This process is directly analogous to an RG flow,"
" where the “microscopic” data distribution is progressively simplified "
"into a “macroscopic” abstract representation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:43
msgid ""
"Just as the RG reveals that all critical points belong to a finite number"
" of universality classes, deep learning shows that a well-trained network"
" automatically discovers the universal structure of the data – the "
"features that generalise across examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:45
msgid "Statistical Physics Foundations: Extensive and Intensive Variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:46
msgid ""
"To fully appreciate the RG analogy, we must distinguish between "
"**extensive** and **intensive** variables in thermodynamics:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:48
msgid ""
"**Extensive variables** (e.g., volume $V$, energy $E$, entropy $S$, "
"number of particles $N$) scale with the size of the system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:49
msgid ""
"**Intensive variables** (e.g., temperature $T$, pressure $p$, chemical "
"potential $\\mu$) are independent of system size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:51
msgid ""
"In the RG flow, the coarse-graining operation reduces the effective "
"number of degrees of freedom—the \"system size\" decreases. Intensive "
"variables like temperature and pressure remain invariant under scaling, "
"while extensive variables like energy and entropy scale linearly with the"
" number of effective spins."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:53
msgid ""
"This distinction is mirrored in deep learning: high-level representations"
" are **intensive**—they capture invariant features of the data (e.g., "
"\"catness\") that are independent of the input's spatial resolution or "
"pixel count—while lower-level features are **extensive**, requiring more "
"units to represent fine-grained details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:55
msgid "The Connection to the Sampling Bottleneck"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:56
msgid ""
"The RG also offers a physical perspective on the sampling problem "
"introduced in later sections. Near a critical point, the correlation "
"length diverges, and the system becomes difficult to simulate – Markov "
"chains mix extremely slowly (critical slowing down). This is precisely "
"the difficulty encountered when sampling from Boltzmann machines that are"
" near their “critical” state, i.e., when the model has learned a rich, "
"multimodal distribution. Understanding this slowdown is central to "
"appreciating why alternative approaches – such as quantum sampling – are "
"needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:58
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:59
msgid ""
"**Coarse-graining** transforms a system at one scale to an equivalent "
"system at a larger scale."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:60
msgid ""
"**Renormalization Group** is the study of how the Hamiltonian changes "
"under coarse-graining, leading to **fixed points** and **universality**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:61
msgid ""
"The RG provides a deep physical analogy for **hierarchical feature "
"learning** in deep neural networks: each layer coarse-grains the features"
" from the layer below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-stat-renormalization.md:62
msgid ""
"Critical slowing down in physical systems mirrors the **sampling "
"bottleneck** in energy-based models, motivating the search for more "
"efficient sampling methods."
msgstr ""

